data.content:
## What breaks

The Cosmos DB provider in EF Core **never had native sync support** — it used sync-over-async wrappers. The deprecation path was:

| Version | Behavior |
|---------|----------|
| EF Core 9 | Sync calls log a warning by default |
| EF Core 10 | Sync calls **throw by default**; opt-in (`CosmosOptionsExtension` / `EnableSyncOverAsync()`) restores them |
| EF Core 11 | Sync-over-async **removed entirely** — the opt-in no longer exists |

In .NET 11, every synchronous LINQ call — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()` — will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime. There is no workaround short of going async.

## The fix

Convert to async end-to-end:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- Callers must propagate `async/await` up the call stack (controllers, services, etc.).
- `Add()` stays synchronous — it only tracks the entity in memory; no I/O occurs until `SaveChangesAsync()`.
- If you have callers that absolutely can't go async, you'll need to restructure them — `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` reintroduces the same deadlock risks the removal was meant to eliminate.
